The paper deals with the Euclidean TSP with neighborhoods problem, which is a problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also presents a novel extension of the $m$-guillotine method, which is a technique used in computational geometry for partitioning a space into smaller regions. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also discusses approximation algorithms, which falls under the scope of cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
